\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bushfires (BFs) and heatwaves (HWs) are two of the most live threatening
 and destructive natural hazards in Australia.
 Taking into consideration the past 100 years, HWs endangering human life
 have been categorized as the most hazardous natural phenomena for people
 in Australia; while BFs ranked fourth 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Haynes2010"

\end_inset

.
 These events have also had important consequences for the Australian economy.
 Considering only building losses, BFs are the third most destructive natural
 hazard, being responsible for 20% of property losses during the period
 1900 to 2003 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "McAneney2009"

\end_inset

.
 (McAneney et al., 2009); on the other hand, HWs massively increase the energy
 demand because of the intense use of air conditioning systems, as well
 as affect the physical integrity of civil infrastructure 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pezza2011"

\end_inset

.
 Since the impacts produced by these events are significant for Australia,
 great effort has been devoted to understand how these events are produced
 from a meteorological perspective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The meteorological variables of bushfire weather (e.g.
 wind, rainfall, air temperature, relative humidity) are governed by large-scale
 synoptic patterns that have particular characteristics in different regions
 of Australia 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BureauofMeteorology2008"

\end_inset

.
 However, the synoptic weather patterns associated with bushfires all have
 hot-dry air advection processes in common, and often the passage of cold
 fronts in initiated bushfire areas 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bradstock2012"

\end_inset

.
 For example, bushfire weather in southeast Australia is characterized by
 an atmospheric high-pressure centre (“high”) in the Tasman Sea and a strong
 cold front arriving from the west 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BureauofMeteorology2008"

\end_inset

.
 The passage of a cold front causes abrupt changes in wind direction converting
 bushfires in extreme or even catastrophic events.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mills2005"

\end_inset

 demonstrated that a strong 850-hPa temperature gradient (associated with
 cold front arrivals) is highly correlated with extreme bushfire events
 in Victoria, Australia (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Localization-of-Victoria"

\end_inset

for lozalization of Victoria).
 The common characteristic of the impacts associated with BFs and HWs in
 this state is the extremely hot and dry environment caused by the northerly
 winds associated with the anticyclone in the Tasman Sea, yet the precursors
 of these events can be quite different.
\end_layout

