\end_inset

demonstrated that an anticyclone (or high) in the Tasman Sea is the principal
 driver of HWs in Victoria.
 In this study, HWs where defined as any three or more consecutive days
 where the maximum temperature was equal or greater than the 90th percentile
 of the monthly climatological mean, provided that the minimum temperature
 did not drop below the 90th percentile in the second and third days.
 HWs were associated to cyclones and anticyclones using a tracking scheme
 (Murray and Simmonds, 1991) for the period 1979-2008.
 The stability of this high in the Tasman Sea supports the dry air advection
 to Southeastern Australia and would prevent the passage of cold fronts,
 which makes this high a “blocking” anticyclone.
 Even though there is a clear relationship between BFs and HWs to my knowledge
 these events have not been investigated in an integrated manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since BF occurrences are associated with hot temperatures and overall dry
 conditions that generally occur during HWs, a logical train of thought
 would be that BFs are likely to be produced during HWs (considering only
 weather variables), however this might not be necessarily true.
 The aim of this article is to compare and contrast the synoptic climatology
 of BFs and HWs in Victoria for the period 1900-2010, discussing some of
 the fundamental differences that lead up to both events.
 This investigation is important because in a bushfire/heatwave prone region
 such as Victoria, weather forecasting and emergency response preparedness
 would greatly benefit to know under which meteorological circumstances
 the risk of having one event or the other (or both) increases.
 
\end_layout

