\begin_layout Subsection
Datasets and definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Major bushfire events in Victoria are officially posted on the State of
 Victoria's Department of Environment and Primary Industries (DEPI, 2014)
 web page; which is the main organization responsible for generating this
 information.
 A general overview of each event since 1851 to 2013 is presented in the
 
\begin_inset Quotes els
\end_inset

Fire & Emergencies
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

 tab; however, specific dates of the events are not always included since
 the information is often described by periods (e.g.
 months within a year when bushfires happened).
 This caveat makes the availability of bushfire dates in this record relatively
 short for the intended research of this study.
 Therefore, an alternative bushfire database had to be employed, in this
 case the 
\begin_inset Quotes els
\end_inset

PerilAUS
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

 developed by Risk Frontiers was selected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Researchers at Risk Frontiers, Macquarie University, have compiled a natural
 hazard occurrence and consequences database (PerilAUS) including events
 such as tropical cyclones, floods and bushfires in Australia, spanning
 information from more than two hundred years to present 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haynes2010"

\end_inset

.
 This database was developed from information compiled from the Sydney Gazzette
 and Sydney Morning Herald newspapers; which started publishing in 1803
 and 1842 respectively (citation).
 The information was validated with local newspapers and official information
 where necessary (Crompton et al., 2010).
 According to (citation), the bushfire subset of this database was initially
 developed in 1991 with information from the Commonwealth Scientific and
 Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) and scientific literature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
PerilAUS establishes two types of bushfire data: reports and events (M.
 Mason, personal communication, August 16, 2013).
 Since the database has a focus on damage, a registered bushfire report
 refers to damage in a particular location.
 On the other hand, a bushfire event refers to the date when bushfires occurred
 —or started—, causing damage in several locations.
 For example, “Black Saturday” a catastrophic bushfire that occurred on
 February 7th 2009 had 18 reports in different locations of Victoria (e.g.
 St.
 Andrews, Weerite, Marysville).
 However, this case is catalogued as a single bushfire event in this database.
 For the purposes of this project, event dates will be used for the analyses
 because it better suits a climatological definition.
 This method has also been used in other investigations to associate bushfires
 with individual large-scale climate processes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Blanchi2012"

\end_inset

.
 This database has recorded 144 bushfire events (Appendix 1) and 580 reports
 in Victoria from the period 1900 to 2010; however, since the information
 was mainly compiled from newspapers, the frequency of bushfires over this
 period is a reflection of human fatalities and building damage rather than
 fire intensity (K.
 Haynes, personal communication, August 13, 2013).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Importantly, while this dataset does not include every bushfire event that
 occurred in the last century, it is not necessary to compile all bushfires
 in order to establish a robust climate signal associated with bushfire
 potential.
 As shown by my results (see Section XXX), the sample is large enough to
 yield statistically significant results, and the knowledge of which modes
 of climate variability are behind the bushfire triggering mechanisms from
 a climate perspective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, heatwave events were defined when the maximum temperature (Tmax)
 and minimum temperature (Tmin) exceeds the 90th percentile for three and
 two consecutive days respectively 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Perkins2012,Sadler2012"

\end_inset

.
 Using this definition, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Sadler2012"

\end_inset

calculated heatwaves considering the season December-January-February-March
 (DJFM) using data from the Bureau of Meteorology Melbourne Regional Office
 Station (Latitude: 37.81 °S Longitude: 144.97 °E), initially for the period
 1970–2013 and subsequently for the period 1857–2013.
 From Sadler’s analysis, this study compiled a database of 96 heatwave events
 in the DJF season in the period 1900-2010 (Appendix 2).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The investigation used climate data from reanalysis products for the intended
 period of analysis (1900–2010).
 Six-hourly daily averages with a 2x2° resolution were selected from the
 Twentieth Century Reanalysis Project (20CR) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Compo2011"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, data from the Met Office Hadley Centre’s sea ice and sea
 surface temperature (SST) data set (HadISST1) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rayner2003"

\end_inset

 were also used; which yields monthly values with a 5x5° resolution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These datasets have common intrinsic limitations (e.g.
 scarce number of observations in the early decades of the 20th century
 globally, less observations in the Southern Hemisphere compared to the
 Northern Hemisphere throughout the entire century, not all variables are
 equally well represented, etc.).
 However, recent results have shown that the 20CR represents well Southeastern
 Australia’s interannual climate variability and teleconnections patterns
 from the late 19th century 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ashcroft2014"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Composite analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Daily anomaly composites were calculated for day -5 to day +5 of the 20th
 century bushfire and heatwave events in order to better understand the
 dynamical evolution of each phenomena.
 It is important to emphasize that bushfire and heatwave events were analysed
 separately, therefore events that had coincident dates -considering the
 three heatwave dates definition plus three additional days to cover bushfires
 that might have occurred because of a lagged effect- were not considered
 in the calculations.
 Since daily SST data was not available for the entire 20th century, the
 anomalies for this variable were calculated with monthly values of the
 HadISST1 dataset for the period 1900-2010.
 Finally, seasonal anomalies composites were calculated for the seasons
 September-November and December-February of every bushfire/heatwave season
 in order to study the climate signal in the preceding season, as well as
 throughout the bushfire and heatwave period.
 A student t-test with a 5% significance level was applied to all the calculated
 anomalies.
\end_layout

