\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main purpose of this study was to compare and contrast the synoptic
 differences between BFs and HWs in Victoria, Australia.
 Additionally, this article has explored the nature of the relationship
 of these events with the Southern Oscillation Index, and its evolution
 over the period 1900-2010.
 The results show that the intuitive idea to associate HWs and BFs 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Bushfire-vs-Heatwave-1900-2010"

\end_inset

 shows that there is not an evident relationship between BFs and HWs during
 the period 1900-2010.
 The weak R coefficient between both events (-0.12) corroborates this finding.
 Even though the correlation coefficient is weak, the negative relationship
 between them provided the first lead to suggest that different mechanisms
 govern these events.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Time-series-of-periods"

\end_inset

 further explores this lead investigating the relationship of BFs and HWs
 with one of the main drivers of Australian climate: El Niño Southern Oscillatio
n (ENSO).
 According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Power1999"

\end_inset

, the impacts ENSO’s teleconnections over Australia experience an inter-decadal
 variability.
 For this reason, the relationship of HWs and BFs with this climate mode
 of variability was analysed using 10-year running means.
 Additionally, for this part of the investigation the period of analysis
 was separated in two to examine the evolution of the relationship with
 ENSO for the first and second half of the century.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Perhaps the most striking result of this research is the complete reversal
 of the correlation coefficient between the SOI and bushfires from -0.66
 to +0.47 in the first and second half of the century respectively (shown
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Time-series-of-periods"

\end_inset

a and b) The reversal does suggest the marked non-lineal nature of ENSO’s
 evolution in time.
 This non-linearity explains how difficult is to find strong correlations
 with bushfire events on a century perspective without a decadal approach.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, heatwaves present a positive relationship for the two
 periods; however, the evolution presented a stronger relationship in the
 second half of the century, shifting from +0.24 to +0.48.
 This does not necessarily mean that a direct relationship with “La Niña”
 events exists, since we have not made a distinction between neutral from
 strong “La Niña” events.
 In fact, our SST composites does not reflect such a relationship (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Sea-surface-temperature-djf"

\end_inset

b), result that agrees with the results of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Boschat2014"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results presented in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:a),-b)-and-daily-temperature-anomalies"

\end_inset

suggest that dry cold fronts, with their associated strong and gusty winds,
 could be even more important than air temperature anomalies in producing
 extreme bushfire events.
 This result agrees with the findings of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mills2005"

\end_inset

for extreme bushfire cases in Victoria.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:a),-b)-and-daily-rh-anomlaies"

\end_inset

 supports the idea that colds fronts play a significant role, since the
 composite of HWs present lower relative humidity anomalies than BFs.
 Evidently, this also means that the long term environmental conditions
 and their influence in preconditioning fuels for BFs are also crucial,
 since the intense air temperature and relative humidity anomalies of HWs,
 do not trigger bushfire events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:a),-b)-and-gz-daily-anomalies"

\end_inset

shows that heat waves in Victoria seem to be associated with a strong wave
 number four leading to a blocking high over the Tasman Sea, a result that
 agrees with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Pezza2007"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, bushfires tend to occur in association with a more transient
 signal from the Indian Ocean and a strong low pressure to the south of
 Australia.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Sea-surface-temperature-djf"

\end_inset

clearly shows how different is the influence of the oceanic component of
 BFs and HWs.
 Although, as we have seen the influence of ENSO with bushfires evolves
 during the century, on average it seems that BFs in Victoria are most likely
 to occur during el “El Niño” events, a result that agrees with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Harris2013"

\end_inset

.
 The argument is based on the statistically significant (using a Student’s
 t test) warm anomalies found in the Tropical Pacific Ocean.
 In contrast, we do not find these anomalies in the SSTs of the HWs composite.
 This result implies that most HWs occur during neutral ENSO events, a result
 that agrees with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Boschat2014"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, HWs in Victoria could be driven instead by the influence of
 regional warm SSTs anomalies in the Tasman Sea and the Great Australia
 Bight.
 These warm anomalies were found to occur analysing the two half’s of the
 century (+5 years each) separately (not shown).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results from the air-temperature anomalies seasonal composites, support
 the argument that “El Niño” events may exert a significant influence over
 bushfire occurrence in Victoria, whereas regional processes associated
 with a warming than average SSTs in the Tasman Sea could be associated
 with the lead up to HWs.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-air-son"

\end_inset

a and Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-air-djf"

\end_inset

a show how hot air teperature anomalies in the Tropical Pacific Ocen might
 be the result of heat-fluxes transfer from the ocean to the atmosphere
 during “El Niño” events, anomalies that coincide with a warmer than average
 Australia.
 This pattern greatly intensifies from spring to summer.
 In contrast, Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-air-son"

\end_inset

b and Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-air-djf"

\end_inset

b illustrate how HWs in Victoria could also have a preconditioning influence
 over the continent in spring; however, the climate signature is clear to
 distinguish a special configuration in the austral summer for Victoria.
 This signature reveals that the heat-flux from the SST’s warming in the
 Tasman and Great Australian Bight, may have an influence over the hot anomalies
 found almost exclusively in the Victorian region, which greatly contrasts
 with a cooler than average Australia.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relative-humidity anomalies seasonal composites shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-rh-son"

\end_inset

 and Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-rh-djf"

\end_inset

 imply that the preconditioning process leading to BFs is more intense and
 prolonged compared to its heatwave counterpart.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-rh-son"

\end_inset

a and Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-rh-djf"

\end_inset

a show how Victoria is a “dry spot” from September to February, a process
 that contributes to the preconditioning of fuel loads before BFs occurrence,
 and has been associated with a positive Indian Ocean Dipole mode 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cai2009"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, according to Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-rh-son"

\end_inset

b and Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-rh-djf"

\end_inset

b HWs present in spring a slight percentage of negative anomalies in Victoria
 that even becomes positive in most of Australia during summer.
 To my knowledge, this particular process has not been addressed in the
 literature and requires further investigation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The differences between bushfire and heatwave weather perhaps are best illustrat
ed when “looking from above”.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:a),-b)-and-gz-daily-anomalies"

\end_inset

has already made this case depicting the differences between the wave trains
 of BFs and HWs on a daily basis with 500-hPa geopotential height composites.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-uwn-djf"

\end_inset

a and Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seasonal-composite-for-uwn-djf"

\end_inset

b present the circulation patterns of 300-hPa zonal wind anomalies of bushfire
 and heatwave seasons respectively.
 For bushfire seasons, the climate signature presents strong westerly anomalies
