\begin_layout Standard
Bushfires (BFs) and heatwaves (HWs) are two of the most dangerous natural
 hazards in Australia.
 These hazards are of particular concern in the southeastern state of Victoria,
 which has endured some of the most catastrophic BF events such as “Black
 Saturday” (07 Feb 2009), and record-breaking HWs like those occurred in
 the “Australian Angry Summer” (December-February 2013).
 Even though BFs and HWs are usually associated with a cause-effect relationship
 in which HWs would produce the conditions for the occurrence of BFs this
 is not completely accurate, given the greater complexity leading to bushfire
 events.
 The aim of this study is to compare and contrast the synoptic signal of
 “pure” BF and HW events in Victoria, Australia.
 To obtain a disentangled signature of these two types of events, daily,
 monthly and seasonal anomaly composites of climate variables were produced
 for BFs and HWs in the period 1900-2010.
 The daily analysis revealed that only 10% of BF events were associated
 with HWs.
 Additionally, this analysis showed that bushfire weather has a dynamic
 profile characterized by a vigorous dry cold front on day zero of the events,
 whereas the synoptic pattern of HWs show persistent and more intense anomalies.
 The monthly and seasonal analysis agreed to show that BFs could be associated
 with “El Nino” events, in contrast to HWs that seem to occur during neutral
 events.
 The anomalous areas found in the seasonal analysis for BF events show potential
 to develop a bushfire weather forecasting tool for Victoria.
 
